2010 Johnson & Johnson children's product recall

From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia


					Jump to:					navigation, 					search

The 2010 Johnson & Johnson children's product recall was a voluntary recall of 43 over-the-counter children's medicines announced by McNeil Consumer Healthcare, a subsidiary of Johnson & Johnson, on April 30, 2010. Medications in the recall included liquid versions of Tylenol, Tylenol Plus, Motrin, Zyrtec, and Benadryl. The products were recalled after it was determined that they "may not fully meet the required manufacturing specifications".[1][2] The recall affected at least 12 countries.[1]



